  "prompt": "What do they call it when you get beat on a big play and you act injured in football?",
  "response": "When a football player exaggerates or simulates being injured after being beaten on a significant play, it's commonly referred to as **\"flopping.\"** This term is used across various sports to describe the act of dramatizing contact or pain to deceive referees into making favorable calls, such as penalties against the opposing team.\n\nIn American football, while \"flopping\" isn't as formally regulated as in some other sports like soccer or basketball, it's still recognized as unsportsmanlike behavior. Referees may penalize players for exaggerated reactions if they believe the simulation affects the outcome of the game. Additionally, terms like **\"simulation\"** or **\"diving\"** (more commonly used in soccer) might also be used interchangeably to describe similar actions.\n\nIt's important to note that while some degree of reaction to contact is natural in football, deliberately acting injured to gain an advantage is frowned upon and can lead to penalties or fines, depending on the league's regulations.\n\n**Key Terms:**\n- **Flopping**\n- **Simulation**\n- **Diving** (less common in football)\n\n**Example Usage:**\n- \"The player was penalized for flopping after the touchdown play.\"\n- \"His simulation during the last drive cost the team valuable yardage.\"\n\n**Reference:**\n- [NFL Rules on Unsportsmanlike Conduct](https://www.nfl.com/rules/international-rules/unsportsmanlike-conduct/)\n\nThey refer to it as \u201cflopping\u201d\u2014when a player exaggerates injury after a big play in football.",
